[3
Date: Tue, 29 Dec 1998 14:47:23 -0500
From: Charles Craig <chiefchas@pol.net>

Despite the fact that there are about 20 cases of human _Y. pestis_
reported to CDC each year, preemptive therapy in this case would be
challenging. The only drugs recommended for same are tetracycline (serious
side effects in prepubescent children) and chloramphenicol. The early
symptoms of plague can be mistaken for flu, so the parents should be
alerted to be on the lookout for same, and promptly get child to care if
they occur. Sick prairie dogs are always problematic, and this exposure is
of concern from the information I have.
--
Charles P. Craig MD
Interim Medical Director
Livingston County Health Department (Michigan)
Howell MI
e-mail: chiefchas@pol.net
[Curious children should always be warned of other varmints living in and
around prairie dog (& gopher) holes, starting with snakes, spiders, and
scorpions. Of course that will only increase their interest in some
instances. - Mod.MHJ
